[{"short_id":"l0rgsa","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/l0rgsa","created_at":"2024-12-03T03:27:40.000-06:00","title":"Domains listening to many other domains in Event-Driven Architecture","url":"https://www.reactivesystems.eu/2024/11/30/not-all-commands-are-equal.html","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eUsually, in an event-driven architecture, events are emitted by one service and listened to by many (1:n). But what if it’s the other way around? If one service needs to listen to events from many other services? I know many people would then use a command - for a command a n:1 relationship, i.e. a service receiving commands from many other services, is quite natural. Of course that’s not event-driven anymore then. Or is it.. what if the command doesn’t require a response? Then again, why is it a command in the first place, maybe we can have n:1 events instead?\nWhat’s your experience with this, how do you solve it in your system if a service needs to listen to events from many other services?\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Usually, in an event-driven architecture, events are emitted by one service and listened to by many (1:n). But what if it's the other way around? If one service needs to listen to events from many other services? I know many people would then use a command - for a command a n:1 relationship, i.e. a service receiving commands from many other services, is quite natural. Of course that's not event-driven anymore then. Or is it.. what if the command doesn't require a response? Then again, why is it a command in the first place, maybe we can have n:1 events instead?\r\nWhat's your experience with this, how do you solve it in your system if a service needs to listen to events from many other services?","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/l0rgsa/domains_listening_many_other_domains","submitter_user":"lutzh","user_is_author":true,"tags":["distributed","programming"]},{"short_id":"rfquja","short_id_url":"https://lobs